title: Satisfaction vs. product
description: Design a mosaic plot to examine the correlation between consumer satisfaction and product type for an electronics company, using 'powderblue' for high satisfaction and 'rosybrown' for low satisfaction.
solution:
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import pandas as pd

count_df = df.groupby(['product_type', 'satisfaction']).size().reset_index(name='counts')
total_counts = count_df.groupby('product_type')['counts'].sum().reset_index(name='total')
count_df = count_df.merge(total_counts, on='product_type')
count_df['proportion'] = count_df['counts'] / count_df['total']

fig = go.Figure()


product_types = count_df['product_type'].unique()
for product_type in product_types:
    subset = count_df[count_df['product_type'] == product_type]
    for _, row in subset.iterrows():
        fig.add_trace(go.Bar(
            x=[product_type],
            y=[row['proportion']],
            name=row['satisfaction'],
            marker_color='powderblue' if row['satisfaction'] == 'High' else 'rosybrown',
            text=str(row['counts']),  # Adding raw count on bar
            hoverinfo='text+name'
        ))

fig.update_layout(
    title='Simulated Mosaic Plot: Consumer Satisfaction by Product Type',
    barmode='stack',
    xaxis_title='Product Type',
    yaxis=dict(title='Proportion', tickformat=',.0%'),
    legend_title='Satisfaction'
)

fig.show()
